snippet.textDisplay:
@Tomas Hull maybe I’ve explained wrong but I was talking about a time eons ago when there was only single cell organisms on earth. 

Not me just research. 🙏🏾

Prokaryotic cells (like bacteria) are very simple cells. They lack a nucleus, sometimes called the control center of the cell. In prokaryotic (PRO-care-ee-ought-ick) cells, the genetic material or DNA is loose inside and is made of a single loop. The loop is called a plasmid. There are few, if any, organelles, and none are bound by cell membranes. The name prokaryote comes from a Greek word meaning "before nuclei." They are the oldest cells on Earth. These cells divide by simple fission. One cell splits into two identical cells. The germs that make us sick are prokaryotic cells.

That doesn’t say the nucleus was separate at one time?
But we did go from single cell organisms to multicellular organisms.. how when ALL LIFE ON EARTH WAS SINGLE CELL AT ONE POINT.

And I could be wrong on this but I swear I watch a documentary on this one time.
We humans don’t know how the nucleus came about or it could be the Organelles?? 


Also found this and I’m sure it’s more me not explaining myself right AT ALL as this is so difficult and amazing how cells actually work
But hopefully it’ll show you I’m not confused. 
Conceding I didn’t explain myself well🙏🏾

This is what I meant.....

Note that eukaryotic cells likely evolved from a symbiotic relationship between two prokaryotic cells, whereby one set of prokaryotic DNA eventually became separated by a nuclear envelope and formed a nucleus. Over time, portions of the DNA from the other prokaryote remaining in the cytoplasmic part of the cell may or may not have been incoporated into the new eukaryotic nucleus.

It wasn’t there before this happened and may or may not have happened because we just don’t know but cells didn’t use to have a walled off DNA Factory 🏭. 🙏🏾
